This screenshot shows the Power BI data model view for the Uber Bookings dashboard, revealing how the report is actually structured behind the scenes — including the central fact table, supporting dimensions, and several helper/disconnected tables used purely for measures and formatting.
Uber — The Central Fact Table
Positioned in the upper-middle of the canvas, Uber is the main transactional table, holding fields like Booking ID, Booking Status, Booking Value, Cancelled Rides by Customer, Cancelled Rides by Driver, and Customer ID. This table connects downward to Calender via a many-to-one relationship (marked with "*" on the Uber side and "1" on the Calender side), which is what drives all the date-based trend visuals (Complete Bookings by Month, Total Distance by Quarter, etc.).
Calender — The Date Dimension
The Calender table sits below Uber and is the model's official date table, containing Date, Month, Month_Number, Quarter, and Quater index (a sort-helper column, similar in purpose to the MonthYearSort column from your retail project). The eye icon next to "Calender" and "Date" indicates these objects are hidden from report view — a common practice once a date table is fully wired into a model, since users interact with slicers rather than the raw table. Calender also connects rightward to the Date table via a bi-directional relationship (shown by the double-arrow icon), both marked "1," suggesting Date functions as a secondary, possibly disconnected date-formatting table.
Date — A Supporting Date Table
On the right side, the Date table holds Date, Date Fields, and Date Order columns. Date Fields and Date Order are greyed out with a "no" icon, meaning they're disabled/hidden fields — likely calculated columns used internally for sorting rather than direct display. This table appears to support consistent date-axis labeling across visuals without duplicating logic in Calender itself.
IMG — A Disconnected Image/Lookup Table
On the lower left, IMG contains just two columns: image and Vehicle_type. It connects upward to MoM_QoQ via a "1"-to-unlabeled relationship. This table is almost certainly used to map vehicle type icons (the Auto, Uber XL, Go Mini graphics seen on the left rail of each dashboard page) so the report can dynamically swap the vehicle image based on the user's selection — a common Power BI technique for icon-driven navigation.
Dist_Rev — A Measure-Holding Table
The Dist_Rev table (left side) contains Dist_Rev, Dist_Rev (hidden field), and another hidden Dist_Rev field, both marked with "no" icons. This is a disconnected "measures table" — a common Power BI pattern where calculated measures (likely toggles between Distance and Revenue views) are grouped together for organizational clarity rather than tied to any physical relationship.
MoM_QoQ — Another Measures Table
Similarly, MoM_QoQ (top left) holds MoM_QoQ, MoM_QoQ Fields, and MoM_QoQ Order, with the latter two hidden. This table appears to power the Month/Quarter toggle buttons seen on the Overview and Distance pages, letting users switch between monthly and quarterly views without needing separate visuals.
_measure — The Central DAX Measures Table
On the top right, _measure is a dedicated, unconnected table holding only calculated measures: Column, Average Distance, Booking Count, Booking Reverse Remove filter, and Complete Bookings. This is best practice in Power BI — keeping all DAX measures in one clean, dedicated table (often called a "measures table") rather than scattering them across physical data tables, making the model easier to navigate and maintain.
Overall Structure
Unlike the retail project's clean star-snowflake schema, this model is intentionally lighter on physical relationships: only two real relationships are visible (Uber → Calender, and Calender ↔ Date), while IMG, Dist_Rev, MoM_QoQ, and _measure function mostly as organizational containers for DAX measures, hidden fields, and icon-switching logic rather than as true relational dimensions. This is a common and efficient design pattern for KPI-heavy dashboards where the goal is dynamic visual switching (vehicle icons, Month/Quarter toggles, Distance/Revenue toggles) rather than deep multi-table drill-down analysis.
